<li id="cite_note-npr-3-7-20-frayer-22"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-npr-3-7-20-frayer_22-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-npr-3-7-20-frayer_22-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-npr-3-7-20-frayer_22-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFFrayer2020" class="citation cs2">Frayer, Lauren (7 March 2020), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.npr.org/2020/03/07/812193930/delhi-riots-aftermath-how-do-you-explain-such-violence"><i>Delhi Riots Aftermath: 'How Do You Explain Such Violence?'<span></span></i></a>, NPR<span class="reference-accessdate">, retrieved <span class="nowrap">7 March</span> 2020</span>, <q>But hundreds of wounded are languishing in understaffed medical facilities. Corpses are still being discovered in drainage ditches. Victims are still dying in hospitals. The death toll has reached 53... Police are facing accusations from victims, witnesses, human rights groups, opposition politicians and Muslim leaders worldwide that they failed to protect Muslim citizens, and in some cases, even incited attacks themselves.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Delhi+Riots+Aftermath%3A+%27How+Do+You+Explain+Such+Violence%3F%27&amp;rft.pub=NPR&amp;rft.date=2020-03-07&amp;rft.aulast=Frayer&amp;rft.aufirst=Lauren&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.npr.org%2F2020%2F03%2F07%2F812193930%2Fdelhi-riots-aftermath-how-do-you-explain-such-violence&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3A2020+Delhi+riots" class="Z3988"></span></span>
