<li id="cite_note-economist-2020-3-12-45"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-economist-2020-3-12_45-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation cs2"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.economist.com/asia/2020/03/12/victims-of-rioting-in-india-are-bashed-by-the-police-and-courts-too">"First the mob, then the law"</a>, <i>The Economist</i>, 12 March 2020<span class="reference-accessdate">, retrieved <span class="nowrap">15 March</span> 2020</span>, <q>During the riots in Delhi, it was only after the high court ordered police to help evacuate wounded people to hospital that the city's 80,000-person police force began to intervene, after 48 hours of arson and murder.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Economist&amp;rft.atitle=First+the+mob%2C+then+the+law&amp;rft.date=2020-03-12&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.economist.com%2Fasia%2F2020%2F03%2F12%2Fvictims-of-rioting-in-india-are-bashed-by-the-police-and-courts-too&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3A2020+Delhi+riots" class="Z3988"></span></span>
